What is Spring MVC?
  Spring MVC is the web framework module of Spring that implements the Model-View-Controller design pattern
  It sits on top of the Java Servlet API and handles the full HTTP request-response lifecycle
  Every incoming HTTP request goes through a central dispatcher, gets routed to the right controller, processed, and a response is returned
  Spring Boot auto-configures Spring MVC with sensible defaults — zero XML, zero web.xml needed
  Spring WebFlux is the reactive alternative introduced in Spring 5 — non-blocking, event-driven, built on Project Reactor

MVC Pattern — What Each Part Does
  Model — the data. A POJO, a Map, or a domain object that carries data between controller and view
  View — the presentation. Can be HTML (Thymeleaf), JSON (REST), XML, PDF, or any rendered output
  Controller — the coordinator. Receives the request, calls the service layer, prepares the model, returns a view or response body

Request Lifecycle — Text Diagram:
  Browser / Client
       │
       │  HTTP Request (GET /api/orders/1)
       ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                   DispatcherServlet                             │
  │              (Front Controller — single entry point)            │
  │                                                                 │
  │  1. Receives ALL requests mapped to "/"                         │
  │  2. Delegates to HandlerMapping → finds the right controller    │
  │  3. Delegates to HandlerAdapter → invokes the controller method │
  │  4. Receives ModelAndView back from controller                  │
  │  5. Delegates to ViewResolver → resolves view name to template  │
  │  6. Renders view / writes JSON response body                    │
  └────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                               │
          ┌────────────────────┼─────────────────────┐
          ▼                    ▼                      ▼
  ┌───────────────┐   ┌─────────────────┐   ┌────────────────────┐
  │HandlerMapping │   │  HandlerAdapter │   │   ViewResolver     │
  │               │   │                 │   │                    │
  │ Maps URL to   │   │ Invokes method  │   │ Resolves view name │
  │ controller    │   │ handles args,   │   │ to actual template │
  │ method        │   │ return value    │   │ (Thymeleaf, JSON)  │
  └───────────────┘   └────────┬────────┘   └────────────────────┘
                               │
                               ▼
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │    Your Controller  │
                    │  @GetMapping("/1")  │
                    │  findOrder(Long id) │
                    └──────────┬──────────┘
                               │
                               ▼
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │   Service Layer     │
                    │   orderService      │
                    │   .findById(id)     │
                    └──────────┬──────────┘
                               │
                               ▼
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │  Repository / DB    │
                    └──────────┬──────────┘
                               │
                               ▼ (response travels back up)
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │  JSON / HTML sent   │
                    │  back to client     │
                    └─────────────────────┘


  FILTER CHAIN (runs before DispatcherServlet):
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────
  Request → [Filter1] → [Filter2] → [Filter3] → DispatcherServlet
  Response← [Filter1] ← [Filter2] ← [Filter3] ← DispatcherServlet

  Filters handle: CORS, authentication, logging, compression, encoding

  Interceptor vs Filter — Flow Diagram:
  Request
     │
     ▼
  [Servlet Filter]          ← Servlet API, runs BEFORE DispatcherServlet
     │                        Access: raw HttpServletRequest/Response
     │                        Use for: auth, CORS, encoding, rate limiting
     ▼
  DispatcherServlet
     │
     ▼
  [HandlerInterceptor]      ← Spring MVC, runs INSIDE DispatcherServlet
     │  preHandle()           Access: handler (controller method), ModelAndView
     ▼                        Use for: auth token check, logging, audit
  Controller Method
     │
     ▼
  [HandlerInterceptor]
     │  postHandle()          ← after controller, before view render
     ▼
  View Rendered
     │
     ▼
  [HandlerInterceptor]
     │  afterCompletion()     ← after everything, even on exception
     ▼
  [Servlet Filter]           ← response passes back through filter chain
     │
     ▼
  Response to Client

Spring Boot Auto-Configuration for MVC:
    Spring Boot detects spring-boot-starter-web on classpath and auto-configures everything
    No DispatcherServlet registration needed — Boot registers it automatically at /
    No ViewResolver bean needed for REST — MappingJackson2HttpMessageConverter handles JSON automatically
    WebMvcAutoConfiguration applies sensible defaults — content negotiation, static resources, error handling

<!-- pom.xml — all you need -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
</dependency>

# application.yml — common MVC settings
server:
  port: 8080
  servlet:
    context-path: /app        # all URLs prefixed with /app

spring:
  mvc:
    format:
      date: yyyy-MM-dd        # global date format
  jackson:
    default-property-inclusion: non_null   # exclude nulls from JSON
    serialization:
      write-dates-as-timestamps: false

